    {
      "id": "f09f401ad6d64102f78d2648524164e86f377efc",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 177,
        "name": "John Hammond",
        "email": "jhammond@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "jhammond"
      },
      "date": "2014-05-09 18:38:00.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nWhat if linux/types.h is included after posix-types.h?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "dc29e2bb4ea1e4611fa7ec66107f7dddec21db44",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2014-05-12 19:32:17.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\n> What if linux/types.h is included after posix-types.h?\n\nThat problem exists independent of this patch, since the presence or absence of <linux/types.h> does not make HAVE_LINUX_TYPES_H magically get set in userspace.  That is just an artifact of our build process that other userspace packages won't have.\n\nI agree there is still a potential issue, but this at least fixes the problem so that e2fsprogs can be built.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "a6046ec5614dec156c46f0c72db5bb0cd3f0e3c1",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 109,
        "name": "Christopher J. Morrone",
        "email": "morrone2@llnl.gov",
        "username": "morrone"
      },
      "date": "2014-05-12 23:20:18.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1\n\nThis patch removes defines like HAVE___S8, but leaves behind dead code in the form of all of the consumers of those defines.\n\nI can perhaps get on board with using the __[su]XX style types in user space for ioctl structs, even though I think C99 style would really be saner.  But I think that we need to then have the Lustre headers in user space perform the correct inlude:\n\n#include <linux/types.h>\n\nI do not think our first move should be to define those values ourselves.  If you look at our definitions, I would say there is a pretty reasonable probably that we aren't doing them correctly for all architectures.  Sure, we hacked it once for PPC, but what about all the rest?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "2be7bcbbe358e90dfd8872670100b3dc4fc64926",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 109,
        "name": "Christopher J. Morrone",
        "email": "morrone2@llnl.gov",
        "username": "morrone"
      },
      "date": "2014-05-12 23:23:15.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\n(1 comment)",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "b64edd20797a173bd4be19f6571986db89d9d135",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2014-05-13 00:36:20.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nThe reason I'm hesitant to include <linux/types.h> in userspace is that this is not guaranteed to be installed. This behaviour is similar to what e2fsprogs is doing. The reason to keep the #ifdef HAVE___U32 is to avoid clashes with the ext2_types.h header - I've just sent a patch upstream to get those headers to also #define these constants to avoid name clashes. \n\nThe other option would be to always include <linux/types.h> instead if making it conditional, and then install our own header that #defines _LINUX_TYPES_H to avoid later name clashes.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "8f1abbe56844af9e289aefce2f2847dea5110de9",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 109,
        "name": "Christopher J. Morrone",
        "email": "morrone2@llnl.gov",
        "username": "morrone"
      },
      "date": "2014-05-13 00:59:41.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nWe clearly have a dependency on linux/types.h, so trying to pretend that we don't seems like the wrong way to do.\n\nUnder what situations would linux/types.h be missing in user space?  Can we fix that by having the correct kernel header dependencies expressed in our packages?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "aee273b415cdb2f027d474a5a0558fd26100b39b",
      "author": {
